Happy New Year! Now is a great time to look back on the year and ask the difficult questions to help yourself improve and prepare for the year ahead. How was performance relative to my benchmark? is my benchmark still appropriate? what factors drove my out/underperformance? what decisions/action did I take at major infection points or sentiment reversals? did my active management add value to my performance? Am I trading too much? too little? what was my biggest mistake of the year? what can I do to avoid making the same mistake in the future? what are my implied return/volatility expectations? where is my highest/lowest conviction? does my positioning accurately reflect these views? which positions would be first to sell in a pinch? am I better off exiting now? what levels am I looking to reduce exposure? what stocks are on my close watch list? what stocks have been on watch for too long? do i have exposure to the major themes/trends driving growth narratives? @Stocktwits + $SPY $QQQ

Discipline and Process. Hold yourself accountable for your actions. Pretend someone is looking over your shoulder and would question every trade that you place. If that person says "why the hell did you do that?" and you do not have a consistent and logical response, there is a problem. It is difficult, but much easier when you start putting things on paper and actually defining your process and how/why you make decisions. Start by making a list of stocks that you are comfortable with, know how they trade, know who owns/trades them and why, and ignore everything else. Who cares about the SPAC of the day, if not on your list, it does not exist.  A trade journal is a good way to start. You are largely on your own in this game and a huge aspect is controlling your emotions and having true conviction is reliant on you defeating your inner urge to puke or take profits too soon or buy at the exact wrong time. Have a plan and know your levels/risk. $STUDY @Stocktwits
